# clemensschulz.com — Site Structure & Build Reference

> Context for Claude Code. This documents the structure, page templates, and intended build of a personal photography portfolio site for **Clemens Schulz**, a hobby photographer who wants to share his images and something about his life. Read fully before generating code.
>
> The visual design is adapted from a reference editorial-portfolio site (monochrome, image-first, Cambon-style display serif over a system sans). That design direction is well-suited to a photo portfolio and is carried over here; the content model and routes have been redesigned for a photographer, not a brand/celebrity portfolio.

## Overview

Personal portfolio for Clemens Schulz — a hobby photographer. The site has two jobs: **show his photographs** (organized by the trips and places where they were taken) and **tell a bit about him** (his life, how he got into photography, the gear he uses, and short written notes about individual images). It is content-light and image-heavy: photographs carry the experience, text stays brief and personal.

- **Nature:** Largely static, personal site. No e-commerce, no auth, no user accounts.
- **Primary content type:** Image galleries grouped by **trip / location**, plus a small number of written pages (about, blog, contact, gear).
- **Tone:** Personal and understated — a passionate amateur sharing his work, not a commercial brand.

## Global Layout

Every page shares an identical header and footer. Only the central content block changes.

### Header / Navigation
- Site wordmark or simple logo "Clemens Schulz" (links to `/`). Plain text set in the display face is fine — no graphic logo required.
- Navigation, kept deliberately simple. Suggested grouping:
  - **Galleries** → list of trips/places (links to `/galleries`, and/or a dropdown of recent trips)
  - **About** → `/about`
  - **Journal** → `/journal` (blog / notes on individual photos)
  - **Gear** → `/gear`
  - **Contact** → `/contact`
- Optional social icons (e.g. Instagram) if Clemens wants them — otherwise omit to keep it minimal.

### Footer
- Name / short tagline (e.g. "Clemens Schulz — Photography").
- Optional social icon(s).
- Legal links: **Impressum** (`/imprint`) and **Datenschutzhinweis** (`/privacy`). These are required for a privately operated site in Germany — keep them.
- Optional copyright line, e.g. "© {year} Clemens Schulz. All photographs are my own."

## Routes / Sitemap

```
/                         Homepage — brief intro + featured images, entry into galleries
/galleries                Index — list of all trips/places, each linking to its gallery
/galleries/{slug}         Trip gallery detail (one per trip/location)
/about                    About / life story
/journal                  Journal index — list of posts/notes
/journal/{slug}           Individual journal post (notes on a photo or trip)
/gear                     Equipment page — cameras, lenses, etc.
/contact                  Contact page
/imprint                  Legal — Impressum
/privacy                  Legal — Datenschutzhinweis
```

Slugs should be clean and human-readable, e.g. `/galleries/fulda`, `/galleries/stuttgart`, `/journal/why-i-shoot-film`. Treat the slug as the stable identifier; derive it from the trip/post title.

## Page Templates

There are five distinct templates.

### 1. Homepage (`/`)
- Optional full-width hero image or a short slideshow of a few favourite shots.
- One or two lines of personal intro (who Clemens is, what he photographs).
- A small selection of featured trips or images that link through into the galleries.
- Standard header + footer.

### 2. Galleries Index (`/galleries`)
- Page heading (e.g. *TRIPS* or *GALLERIES*).
- A grid (or clean vertical list) of trips. Each entry shows a representative cover photo, the trip/place name, and optionally the year/location.
- Each entry links to its gallery detail page (`/galleries/{slug}`).
- No long body copy — the heading plus the trip grid.

Current galleries (to scaffold with — extend as Clemens adds trips):

| slug | title | location |
|---|---|---|
| `fulda` | Fulda | Fulda, Germany |
| `stuttgart` | Stuttgart | Stuttgart, Germany |

### 3. Trip Gallery Detail (`/galleries/{slug}`)
- Heading: the trip/place name (e.g. `# FULDA` or `# Stuttgart`).
- A short intro: 1–3 sentences about the trip — when, where, what it was like.
- A stack or grid of large photographs from that trip, flowing vertically. Optional per-image captions.
- Optional small meta line (location, date, camera used) — keep subtle.
- No prev/next required, though a link back to `/galleries` is helpful.

### 4. Written Page (`/about`, `/gear`, `/contact`)
- Single-column, readable measure.
- **About:** heading + multi-paragraph life story (how he got into photography, what draws him to it), optionally a portrait photo.
- **Gear:** heading + a simple list or short prose describing his cameras, lenses, and any other equipment. A plain list is fine here (this is one of the few places a list is natural).
- **Contact:** heading + how to reach him (email link, social). Keep it simple; a contact *form* is optional and, if added, must follow the form-handling caveat in Build Notes.

### 5. Journal Index + Post (`/journal`, `/journal/{slug}`)
- **Index:** heading + a reverse-chronological list of posts. Each item shows title, date, and optionally a thumbnail and a one-line excerpt.
- **Post:** heading (post title) + date + body copy (notes about a photo, a trip, or a thought), interleaved with the relevant image(s). Same readable single-column measure as the written pages.

The galleries follow the **index → detail pattern**; the journal follows an **index → post pattern**. Both reuse the same global chrome.

## Suggested Data Model

The site reduces to a few simple content types:

```
Trip (gallery)
  slug            e.g. "fulda"         (stable identifier)
  title           e.g. "Fulda"
  location        e.g. "Fulda, Germany" (optional)
  date            e.g. "2024-09"        (trip date, for ordering/labels)
  intro           short description, 1–3 sentences, optional
  cover           image used on the galleries index
  photos[]        ordered list of Photo

Photo
  url
  alt             meaningful description
  caption         optional short note
  meta            optional { location, date, camera, lens }

JournalPost
  slug
  title
  date
  body            richtext, interleaved with images
  images[]        { url, alt, caption }

AboutPage   (singleton)   bio richtext + optional portrait
GearPage    (singleton)   list/prose of equipment
ContactPage (singleton)   contact details (+ optional form)
```

Plus two static **legal** pages (`/imprint`, `/privacy`).

## Design Plan

> The visual design is adapted from an editorial-portfolio reference and is a strong fit for a photography site: strictly monochrome, image-first, quiet chrome. Where the reference site used a commercially licensed display serif (Cambon), this plan uses a free alternative (Fraunces) so the site can be built without licensing cost. Measured layout values from the reference are kept as a sensible starting point; adjust to taste for a personal site.

### Design Principles
- **Strictly monochrome.** Black and white only, no accent color. Color enters only through the photographs.
- **Image-first.** Large-format photography dominates; UI elements stay minimal and never compete with the work.
- **Editorial, not corporate.** Generous whitespace, confident typography, no cards, no shadows, no rounded "app" styling.
- **Type contrast as the signature.** A flared/old-style display serif for headlines against a clean system sans for body, nav, and UI.
- **Italic as a deliberate device.** Use italic for captions, labels, and secondary headlines — sparingly, never for the main H1.
- **Quiet chrome.** Header/footer recede; the photographs own the viewport.
- **Personal, not flashy.** This is one person sharing his work — keep motion and effects restrained.

### Color Tokens
| Token | Value | Usage |
|---|---|---|
| `--color-black` | `#000000` | Body text, footer background |
| `--color-white` | `#FFFFFF` | Page background, text on dark/hero |
| `--color-text-primary` | `rgb(0,0,0)` | All body copy |
| `--color-text-on-dark` | `rgb(255,255,255)` | Text over a photo/hero background |
| `--color-footer-bg` | `#000000` | Footer |

No brand accent color by design — resist adding one.

### Typography
Two roles: a **display serif** for headlines and a **system-UI sans** (`system-ui, -apple-system, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif`) for all body, nav, and UI text. The system stack is free and needs no substitution.

| Element | Font | Size | Weight | Style | Line-height | Transform | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| H1 (page title) | display serif | 64px | 400 | normal | 72px | uppercase | margin: 20px 0 10px |
| H2 (secondary headline) | display serif | 64px | 400 | italic | 72px | uppercase | margin: 20px 0 40px |
| Body / copy | system-UI | 15px | 300 | normal | 24px | none | |
| Body base | system-UI | 16px | 400 | normal | 20px | none | |
| Nav links | system-UI | 15px | 400 | normal | 20px | uppercase | padding: 10px 15px |
| Photo caption / label | system-UI | 15px | 300 | italic | 24px | none | margin-top: 16px |
| Hero caption | system-UI | 18px | 300 | italic | 24px | none | white on hero |

These are desktop values — define responsive overrides for tablet/mobile (headings smaller, grids collapse to one column).

### Free Display Font (recommended)

Use a free, OFL-licensed (commercial-use-OK) **flared / old-style serif** for the display role — *not* a slab serif, which has the wrong personality.

1. **Fraunces** (recommended) — open-source display serif (Undercase Type / Google Fonts, SIL OFL). Variable font with weight, optical-size (`opsz`), softness (`SOFT`), and wonk (`WONK`) axes. For the 64px H1/H2, push `opsz` toward its high end for proper display contrast.
2. **Caladea** (safe/neutral) — OFL serif, quieter and more conservative; use if a more restrained headline is preferred.

```css
/* Google Fonts (variable) */
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Fraunces:opsz,wght@9..144,400&display=swap');

:root {
  --font-display: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
  --font-body: system-ui, -apple-system, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif;
}
```

On large headings set a high optical size, e.g. `font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 144;`. Self-host or load with `font-display: swap` to avoid layout shift.

### Layout & Grid
**Global container:** max-width `1440px`; horizontal margin `~56.6px` each side (≈5%); main content fills 100% of container width.

**Header / nav:** `position: fixed`, `z-index: 25`, height `80px`, transparent background overlaying content. `display: flex`, `justify-content: space-between`, `align-items: center`. Wordmark left, nav right with each link `padding: 10px 15px`. Because the header is fixed and transparent, **every page must reserve its own top padding** (~140px) so content clears it.

**Hero (homepage):** optional full-width image or short slideshow, up to `100vh`. Any caption bottom-aligned, italic, white.

**Galleries index grid:** two columns (`1fr 1fr`), gap `60px`; section padding `140px 0`. Each cover image ~4:5 portrait or a consistent ratio of your choice; trip name as an italic label below the image (`margin-top: 16px`, 15px/300). Collapses to one column on mobile.

**Trip gallery detail:** single column, centered. Title, short intro, then large photos stacked vertically near full content-width (allow occasional full-bleed). Keep consistent spacing between images; don't randomly mix crop ratios within one gallery.

**Written / journal pages:** single column at a comfortable reading measure (~600–720px), left-aligned body copy.

**Footer:** background `#000000`, wrapper padding `60px 0`, `display: flex`. Name/tagline, optional social icon, legal links white on black.

