### Motion (use sparingly)
- Soft fade / fade-up on images as they enter the viewport.
- Subtle hover on links (underline grow or slight opacity shift) — nothing flashy.
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.

### What to Avoid
- Drop shadows, heavy borders, rounded-corner "cards", gradients, generic SaaS/dashboard aesthetics.
- Decorative accent colors or multiple competing display fonts.
- Dense UI, sidebars, or anything that distracts from the photographs.

## Build Notes for Implementation
- Content changes infrequently and is mostly static → a static site generator (Astro, Next.js static export, Eleventy) or a lightweight headless/file-based CMS fits well. Trips and journal posts map cleanly to content collections / Markdown files with frontmatter.
- Prioritize **image performance**: responsive `srcset`/`sizes`, lazy-load below-the-fold images, eager-load the hero/LCP image, and serve modern formats (`.webp`/`.avif`). For a photographer's site this is the single most important technical concern.
- Always provide meaningful `alt` text per photo (place + subject).
- Keep the German legal pages (`/imprint`, `/privacy`) — required for a privately operated German site.
- The 64px/72px headings and 140px section padding are desktop values — add responsive overrides; two-column grids collapse to one column on mobile.
- Accessibility: maintain WCAG AA contrast (easy with the monochrome palette), full keyboard navigability with visible focus states, semantic landmarks (`header`, `nav`, `main`, `footer`), and correct heading order.
- **Contact form (only if added):** do not wire up form submission to a third-party endpoint or add credentials/integrations without Clemens explicitly confirming the provider and details. A plain `mailto:` link is the simplest, safest default.
- Replace all placeholder trip names, journal posts, gear, and bio copy with Clemens's real content before launch — the lists and example slugs here are scaffolding, not final content.